Best Practices for Fully Qualified Keys

Use fully qualified keys (FQK) to help Data Cloud accurately interpret data ingested from different data sources.

To use FQKs, configure key qualifier fields for all data lake object (DLO) fields that contain a key value. The field can be a primary key or a foreign key field.
When fields from multiple DLOs are mapped to the same data model object (DMO) field, all the DLO fields must have key qualifier fields. In this example, the primary key fields from Contact and SFMC Subscriber DLOs are mapped to the same DMO field, Individual.Id. So both DLO fields must have a key qualifier field configured.
When you create a calculated insight, use key qualifier fields in table joins and dimensions to ensure data accuracy. Key qualifier fields also enable Data Cloud to interpret your insight correctly when it’s combined with other DMOs in segments and activations.
When you enable FQK in an existing org, update your existing calculated insights to add key qualifier fields to table joins and dimensions.
To ensure that data from multiple DMOs are combined and interpreted accurately, use key qualifier fields in all table joins in the query SQL. Use the COALESCE() function on key qualifier fields to ensure null-safe joins.
In Tableau, use key qualifier fields in table joins and ad hoc table joins. Use the IFNULL() function on key qualifier fields to ensure null-safe joins.
